explanation:
For determining whether any operations in OS_CountSemGetInfo are dead (i.e., executed but removable without changing program behaviour) the next analyzer must know the exact semantics and side-effects of the following symbols:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER: This macro may perform an early return or other control-flow/diagnostic actions. Whether it prevents later operations from executing (or changes observable behaviour) is essential to judging if subsequent statements are dead.

- memset: The function zeroes the caller-provided count_prop. To decide if that write is redundant (dead) you must know what later writes (by strncpy, assignment, or the Impl routine) cover, and whether the zeroing affects any observable bytes.

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Governs whether the inner block executes (based on its return) and initializes the token. Its behavior determines reachability of most operations in the function and thus whether they are removable.

- OS_SUCCESS: The value tested after OS_ObjectIdGetById; needed to interpret the success path vs failure path and whether inner operations execute.

- OS_LOCK_MODE_GLOBAL, LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: Constants passed to OS_ObjectIdGetById; their values/semantics may change which object/table is looked up and thus the observable effects of the function.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Macro (or function) used to get the record from OS_global_count_sem_table using the token. Its exact expansion/behavior is required to know whether accessing record (and subsequent reads) have side-effects or are redundant.

- OS_global_count_sem_table: The object table referenced by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; its layout/contents determine what record->name_entry and record->creator read and whether those reads are meaningful.

- OS_common_record_t: The record type returned by the table access; the analyzer must know the locations and sizes of name_entry and creator to determine what strncpy/assignment do and whether they overwrite meaningful data.

- OS_count_sem_prop_t: The caller-provided struct type (size and name field length) is required to know what memset and strncpy affect and whether any bytes remain in count_prop that are only set by the memset (i.e., to determine if the memset is dead).

- strncpy: Standard copy semantics (including null-termination behavior given the length used) are needed to know which bytes of count_prop->name are set by this call and whether the prior memset or later Impl writes make it redundant.

- OS_CountSemGetInfo_Impl: This implementation routine takes the token and count_prop and may write into count_prop (or depend on record contents). If it fully initializes count_prop or otherwise makes earlier stores unnecessary, that would make earlier operations dead. Its side-effects must be known.

- OS_ObjectIdRelease: Releases the token and has observable side-effects on the object system; removing this call could change program behaviour even if other writes are redundant, so its semantics are required to determine if it is removable.

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: This symbol is used by OS_CountSemGetInfo_Impl and by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET expansions in many implementations; knowledge of how token->index is derived is necessary to reason about table accesses and whether reads of record fields are meaningful.

- OS_object_token_t: The token type and its lifetime/contents are required to reason about initialization by OS_ObjectIdGetById, usage by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET and OS_CountSemGetInfo_Impl, and correct use/release. Without knowing the token layout/semantics one cannot conclude that token-related operations are dead.

Providing these symbols (macros, types, constants, and functions) allows the next analyzer to determine which stores/reads and calls are necessary for externally observable behaviour and therefore whether any operation in OS_CountSemGetInfo constitutes dead code.
